-p8q-tSJqkoIMgcQ ) were the Aggregators on one side and consumer-focused su=
bscription-driven publishers on the other. The former filter the deluge of =
mostly crap free content, while the latter have to continually work to earn=
 not just a reader=E2=80=99s attention but their money as well.

The NBA and other major sports are, to be clear, not newspapers: there is o=
nly one place you can watch LeBron James or Steph Curry or Giannis Antetoko=
unmpo. Moreover, the pay-TV bundles still exists, and still needs inventory=
: RSN losses will likely be covered by national TV deal gains. It would beh=
oove the league and its partners, though, particularly ESPN, to study compa=
nies and sports that don=E2=80=99t have as much differentiation or as many =
structural advantages. What would it mean to make the NBA far more fan-frie=
ndly? How much return might come from story-telling and myth-making instead=
 of simply playing to Twitter?

The impact of the Internet on industry after industry, medium after medium,=
 is to give customers choice: the entities that thrive work diligently to b=
uild a direct connection with customers and increase the attractiveness of =
the product, and the rest get ground up in the grist of Aggregation.

